An easy, transport and py2/3 independent way to get case insensitivity here is to simply return a lowercase-key dict - and document that behaviour so that consumers of this method know to retrieve keys as lower case:
```
if not case_sensitive_keys:
        # if duplicate case insensitive keys are passed in, raise error
        new_args_dict = {}
        duplicate_keys = set()
        for key in args_dict.keys():
            new_key = key.lower()
            if new_key in new_args_dict:
                raise ValueError(
                    "Duplicate key in connection string: {}".format(new_key)
                )
            new_args_dict[new_key] = args_dict[key]
       
        return new_args_dict
```
This isn't as fancy as the requests implementation - but at least will be consistent across all environments

Originally there was an `str` interface:
```
baseObject=str(self.dn)
```
Later I changed it to passing just `DistinguishedName` instance. `LDAPSearchRequest` instance (as any other `pureber`/`pureldap` instances) use `to_bytes` function to get bytes representation of an object. It uses `toWire` method if it is defined for an object. But now there are no `toWire` methods in `distinguishedname` classes so I pass a unicode string.

I just thought that I can extend `to_bytes` function to use `getText` method for `distinguishedname` objects. So the interface will be the same and `to_bytes` will look something like this:
```
def to_bytes(value):
    if hasattr(value, 'toWire'):
        return value.toWire()
    if hasattr(value, 'getText'):
        return value.getText().encode('utf-8')
    if isinstance(value, six.text_type):
        return value.encode('utf-8')
    return bytes(value)
```

