Since most people (and automatminer) will `set_n_jobs` **after instantiation**, this won't function as intended - it will just be superceded. We should keep this in the `__init__`, but should also override the `BaseFeaturizer.set_n_jobs` method; e.g., 

```
class RoostFeaturizer(BaseFeaturizer):
    def __init__(...)
        ...
        self.set_n_jobs(1)

    def set_n_jobs(self, n_jobs):
        if n_jobs != 1:
            warnings.warn("Multiprocessing n_jobs invalid for pytorch. Please use <some option in __init__> to set the number of jobs. Setting n_jobs to 1...")
        self._n_jobs = 1
```

There should also be a test which directly tests this. I can see this causing a lot of problems in the future if someone tries to use n_jobs and it doesn't work as intended. It's one of those very sneaky things which can turn into a troubleshooting nightmare

