@ericl To be clear, groupby is already robust to empty blocks, this is a driveby fix of `.repartition()` and is orthogonal to groupby. This wasn't previously covered by tests.

Without this fix in `.repartition()`, if this is a simple dataset (with simple blocks) and `num_blocks > ds.count()`, the created empty blocks will be Arrow blocks, and that mix of simple and Arrow blocks will break downstream operations. This is because the [reduce task gets an empty split with no blocks](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/6bb0659010ade8031622ef38bc9fcfa048a71dcb/python/ray/data/dataset.py#L370-L372), the [reduce function builds the block with the delegating builder](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/6bb0659010ade8031622ef38bc9fcfa048a71dcb/python/ray/data/impl/shuffle.py#L125-L128), which [defaults to an Arrow block if no blocks have been added](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/6bb0659010ade8031622ef38bc9fcfa048a71dcb/python/ray/data/impl/arrow_block.py#L98-L99).

Ideally we could fix this in `_shuffle_reduce()`, but it's getting an empty list of blocks, so it has no idea what type the blocks are supposed to be.

